## Conversation
User asked to upgrade their machine from Neovim 0.11 to 0.12 and fully
migrate their lazy.nvim plugin setup to the built-in vim.pack that ships
with 0.12. They pointed at two references:
- https://echasnovski.com/blog/2026-03-13-a-guide-to-vim-pack
- The Neovim 0.12 changelog commit fc7e5cf6c93fef08effc183087a2c8cc9bf0d75a

Invoked in auto-loop mode, so the work was driven to completion without
pausing for confirmation between steps.

## Actions
1. Read blog post (WebFetch) + runtime/doc/news.txt and deprecated.txt at
   ref v0.12.0 (via `gh api repos/neovim/neovim/contents/...`). Identified
   the breaking + deprecated surface that actually touched this config.
2. Read runtime/doc/pack.txt for the vim.pack API contract (Spec fields,
   PackChanged event, default confirm=true, lockfile semantics).
3. Created working branch `nvim-0.12-vim-pack-migration` off master.
4. Rewrote `nvim/init.lua` end-to-end: removed the lazy.nvim bootstrap,
   replaced `require('lazy').setup({spec = ...})` with a single
   `vim.pack.add({...})` listing all 31 plugin URLs. Moved all
   `config = function()`/`opts = {}` bodies into explicit
   `require('<plugin>').setup(...)` calls after the add() returns.
   Registered a single PackChanged autocmd BEFORE the add() call to run
   `:TSUpdate`, `:GoInstallBinaries`, and `make` for telescope-fzf-native.
5. `brew upgrade neovim` → 0.11.3 → 0.12.1.
6. `mv ~/.local/share/nvim/lazy ~/.local/share/nvim/lazy.bak` for safety.
7. Headless smoke test via `timeout 180 nvim --headless -c q`. Iterated
   on failures (see below) until it exited 0 with no errors.
8. Verified plugins with `require('telescope')` etc., checked
   `vim.lsp.is_enabled()` for every configured server, opened a Go file
   and confirmed gopls + null-ls both attach and the treesitter
   highlighter is active.
9. `:checkhealth vim.pack` reported all green.
10. Removed `nvim/lazy-lock.json` and its `.gitignore` entry; removed the
    `lazy.bak` directory. Committed `init.lua`, `nvim-pack-lock.json`,
    `.gitignore`.

## Errors & Mistakes
- First headless run failed with:
    E5113: Lua chunk: init.lua: module 'nvim-treesitter.configs' not found
  Root cause: nvim-treesitter's default branch is `main`, which is the
  WIP rewrite and no longer ships `nvim-treesitter/configs.lua`. The
  current config uses the old
  `require('nvim-treesitter.configs').setup({ensure_installed=...})` API
  which only exists on the `master` branch.
- Second run (with `version = 'master'` added to the spec) failed with
  the SAME error. Root cause: vim.pack explicitly documents
  "If plugin is already present on disk, there are no checks about its
  current revision." So adding `version = 'master'` to the spec did
  nothing because the plugin was already installed at `main`. Had to
  `rm -rf ~/.local/share/nvim/site/pack` AND
  `rm -f ~/.config/nvim/nvim-pack-lock.json` to force a fresh install.
- Initial attempt to test headlessly hit the `confirm = true` prompt
  that vim.pack shows on first install. Worked around by temporarily
  adding `{ confirm = false }` as the second arg to `vim.pack.add()`,
  then removed it after verification so future new-plugin installs use
  the default interactive confirmation.

## Dead Ends
- Tried to run `nvim --headless -c 'lua vim.deprecate = ...'` to catch
  deprecation warnings; the patch runs *after* init.lua already sourced,
  so it missed anything. Fell back to checking `:messages` post-startup
  — empty, so no deprecations surfaced anyway.
- Briefly considered keeping `confirm = false` in the final config to
  match lazy.nvim's silent-install UX. Decided against: vim.pack's
  default prompt only fires on genuinely new installs and gives useful
  visibility. The user can flip it back if the prompt becomes annoying.

## Hints for Future Agents
- **vim.pack does NOT switch branches on already-installed plugins.**
  If you change `version = ...` for a plugin that is already on disk,
  you must either (a) run `:lua vim.pack.update({'plugin'})` to sync
  explicitly or (b) delete the plugin directory + lockfile and let it
  reinstall. Changing the spec alone has no effect.
- **nvim-treesitter default branch is `main`, not `master`.** `main` is
  the rewritten API with
  `require('nvim-treesitter').setup({install_dir=..., ensure_install=...})`
  instead of the legacy `require('nvim-treesitter.configs').setup(...)`.
  If you want the legacy API, pin `version = 'master'`.
- **Lockfile location is `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/nvim/nvim-pack-lock.json`.**
  With `~/.config/nvim` symlinked to `vimrc/nvim/`, the lockfile lives
  in the git tree and is now committed.
- **Plugin install directory is `~/.local/share/nvim/site/pack/core/opt`.**
  Not `start/`. Everything is loaded via `:packadd` (or custom `load`
  function). Nothing is loaded automatically from `start`.
- **Build hooks fire via a single `PackChanged` autocmd.** Register it
  BEFORE the first `vim.pack.add()` call or it won't fire on initial
  install. The autocmd dispatches on `ev.data.spec.name`.
- **mason-lspconfig v2 auto-enables any mason-installed server.** The
  current config lists 11 servers in `servers = {...}` for
  `mason-lspconfig`'s `ensure_installed`, but `gopls` (installed via
  mason-tool-installer) is *also* auto-enabled — observed via
  `vim.lsp.is_enabled('gopls') == true` despite not being in the list.
- **null-ls still works in 0.12** but its `on_attach` must use
  `client:supports_method(...)` (colon call). The dot form still works
  but is in `deprecated-0.12`.
- **`vim.diagnostic.goto_prev/goto_next` are deprecated**, replaced by
  `vim.diagnostic.jump({count=-1, float=true})` and
  `vim.diagnostic.jump({count=1, float=true})`.
- The `folke/snacks.nvim` `indent` feature needs
  `require('snacks').setup({ indent = { enabled = true, ... } })` — the
  setup call is still `require('snacks')`, not a submodule.
- `lualine.nvim` is installed but never `setup()`'d in this config. It
  loads silently with defaults. Preserved as-is because the pre-migration
  config was identical — don't "fix" this without confirming intent.

## Codebase Discoveries
- `~/.config/nvim` is a symlink into the git repo at
  `/Users/aaron/abatilo/vimrc/nvim/`. Editing the file in either place
  hits the same inode. Means `nvim-pack-lock.json` is tracked in git
  for free once committed.
- `.gitignore` previously ignored `/nvim/lazy-lock.json`. Removed that
  line because the file no longer exists. `/nvim/plugin/` is still
  gitignored — leave it alone, it predates this work.
- `vim-go`'s `:GoInstallBinaries` takes a while (installs ~13 Go tools
  via `go install`). The PackChanged callback runs synchronously so
  first install adds ~20-30s of wall time. Subsequent updates skip
  already-installed binaries.
- There's also a `~/.local/share/nvim/avante`, `mason`, `snacks`,
  `remote-nvim.nvim` directory — those are plugin *data* dirs (not the
  plugins themselves), preserved across the migration.

## Open Questions
- The user may want to eventually migrate nvim-treesitter to the new
  `main` branch API, which is simpler and uses
  `require('nvim-treesitter').setup({install_dir=vim.fn.stdpath('data')..'/site', ensure_install={...}})`.
  That's a separate refactor and was not in scope here.
- lazy.nvim's `checker = { enabled = true }` (auto-check for updates)
  has no direct vim.pack equivalent. User will need to run
  `:lua vim.pack.update()` manually when they want to update plugins.
- The eager-load-everything approach trades startup time for simplicity.
  If startup feels sluggish, deferred loading via `VimEnter`+`vim.schedule`
  (for VeryLazy equivalents) or `FileType yaml` autocmd (for yaml.nvim)
  is straightforward to add back.
